## Firebase

This project was scaffolded with `--firebase`. **Local development uses the emulator suite, offline** — `nx serve <app>` auto-launches the emulators alongside the dev server under the offline project id `demo-<workspaceName>`. No `firebase login`, no cloud project, no `.firebaserc` is needed for development. By design.

**When the user asks to deploy this app — or otherwise connect it to a real Firebase project — walk them through these steps** (from the workspace root inside the devcontainer, where the Firebase CLI is installed):

1. `firebase login` — one-time auth against their Google account (opens a browser).
2. `firebase use --add` — picks a project from their account and writes `.firebaserc`. If they don't have a project yet, create it first (Firebase console or `firebase projects:create <id>`).
3. `firebase apps:sdkconfig WEB <appId> --project <projectId>` — prints the real web config.
4. Paste the returned `firebaseConfig` object into `productionFirebaseConfig` in `apps/<APP>/src/app/firebase.config.ts`.

**Never fabricate `.firebaserc` or the production config** — the Firebase CLI is the source of truth for cloud state. `provideAppFirebase()` throws at bootstrap if production is attempted with an empty config, so silent broken deploys are impossible. Inside the devcontainer, **every interactive terminal shows a self-extinguishing banner** (`tools/firebase-welcome.sh`, sourced via `/etc/profile.d/zz-firebase-welcome.sh`) reminding the user of the recipe until setup is complete — when both `.firebaserc` exists and `productionFirebaseConfig.projectId` is filled, the banner goes silent automatically. The same recipe also lives in the header of `firebase.config.ts` and in the `project-starter:new-project` skill.

## Generator-first, manual last

For anything Nx can generate - apps, libraries, components, services, project config - **use the Nx generator (`nx g ...`); never hand-create and fill files.** Before hand-writing anything structural, check what exists: `nx list <plugin>` / `nx g <generator> --help` (or the `nx-generate` skill / the Nx MCP server). Only fall back to manual file creation when no generator covers the task. **Never guess flags** - verify against `--help` / `nx_docs`.

## Common Commands

```bash
# Generate the next Angular app or library (generator-first!)
yarn nx g @nx/angular:application apps/<app-name> --minimal
yarn nx g @nx/angular:library libs/<lib-name>

# Serve / build / test / lint a project
yarn nx serve <project>
yarn nx build <project>
yarn nx test <project>
yarn nx lint <project>

# Run a target across everything affected by your changes
yarn nx affected -t build test lint
```

## Working with Nx

- For navigating/exploring the workspace, invoke the `nx-workspace` skill first - it has patterns for querying projects, targets, and dependencies.
- When running tasks (build, lint, test, e2e, etc.), always prefer `nx` (`nx run`, `nx run-many`, `nx affected`) over the underlying tooling directly.
- Prefix nx commands with the workspace package manager (`yarn nx ...`) - avoids the globally installed CLI.
- You have access to the Nx MCP server and its tools - use them.
- For Nx plugin best practices, check `node_modules/@nx/<plugin>/PLUGIN.md` (not all plugins have it - proceed without if absent).
- For scaffolding (apps, libs, structure), invoke the `nx-generate` skill FIRST before exploring or calling MCP tools.

